Jeff Langr wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt;  &gt; This goes against the basic design of JUnit, which promotes test
&gt;  &gt; isolation. The only thing I can think of to achieve this is
&gt; System.exit().
&gt; 
&gt; Which is something I had to deal with two days ago, while writing tests
&gt; against a main method. System.exit(), unfortunately, has to be
&gt; &quot;extracted and overridden.&quot; Unless you know of another way.

Actually, I meant invoking System.exit() from within the test at the 
point where the &quot;fatal failure&quot; occurs.

@Test public void ifIFailThenStopThePresses() throws Exception {
     try {
         // body of test
     }
     catch (Exception die) {
         die.printStackTrace();
         System.exit(-1);
     }
     catch (AssertionError die) {
         die.printStackTrace();
         System.exit(-1);
     }
}
